{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563841"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:05:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:05:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16908"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16908"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.1,0.12,0.26,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9598"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"459"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1999"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"9200"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"},{"type":"tags","id":"12942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39364"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man is admitted to the medical ward for management of cellulitis of the left lower leg. During his admission, he has been taking paracetamol and ibuprofen for pain management, and is receiving intravenous flucloxacillin. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications include amlodipine and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medical emergency team is urgently called after he develops sudden onset large volume haematemesis. On examination, he appears pale and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 135/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. An urgent venous blood gas reveals a haemoglobin of 135 g/L (130-180).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activate major haemorrhage protocol","Crossmatch one unit of packed red blood cells","Commence intravenous pantoprazole infusion","Give 500 mL albumin bolus","Request urgent gastroenterology consultation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of large volume upper gastrointestinal bleeding with haemodynamic compromise, indicated by significant tachycardia and hypotension. Despite a normal initial haemoglobin, the clinical picture suggests major blood loss requiring immediate intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe suggested criteria to \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivate a major haemorrhage protocol (MHP)\u003C/strong\u003E according to the Patient Blood Management Guidelines by the National Blood Authority, Australia, are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eclinical suspicion of critical bleeding and \u2265 1 of:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esystolic blood pressure \u0026lt;100 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eheart rate \u0026gt; 100 bpm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epositive FAST (focused assessment with sonography for trauma)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026gt; a litre of estimated blood loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epallor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence, activating the major haemorrhage protocol (MHP) is the most appropriate first step. The normal haemoglobin should not be reassuring as it reflects the pre-bleeding level, and haemodilution has not yet occurred. The protocol ensures rapid access to blood products and triggers a coordinated emergency response from the blood bank, laboratory, and clinical teams.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrossmatch one unit of packed red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient, given the clinical signs of shock and ongoing bleeding. This patient requires emergent blood products through the massive transfusion protocol, which provides a more comprehensive approach with balanced blood products, including plasma and platelets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence intravenous pantoprazole infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is an important adjunctive therapy for upper gastrointestinal bleeding but should not take priority over immediate resuscitation in a shocked patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGive 500 mL albumin bolus\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate in this setting. While albumin is a colloid that theoretically provides better intravascular volume expansion than crystalloids, it offers no advantage over blood products in haemorrhagic shock. More importantly, albumin lacks oxygen-carrying capacity and coagulation factors, which are essential in massive haemorrhage. Additionally, albumin is expensive, and its use in acute resuscitation has not been shown to improve outcomes compared to crystalloids. Ina massive haemorrhage, any fluid resuscitation that is not blood products can worsen dilutional coagulopathy and should not delay blood product administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest urgent gastroenterology consultation\u003C/strong\u003E will be necessary but should not delay resuscitation. Endoscopy is most safely performed after initial haemodynamic stabilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle is that clinical signs of significant blood loss should guide immediate management decisions rather than initial laboratory values, which may be misleading in acute bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial haemoglobin may be normal in acute gastrointestinal bleeding due to delayed haemodilution.","The major haemorrhage protocol should be initiated based on clinical signs of significant blood loss rather than initial haemoglobin.","Early activation of the blood bank and major haemorrhage protocol is critical in managing acute large-volume gastrointestinal bleeding."],"references":["National Blood Authority. Patient blood management guideline: adults \u2013 critical bleeding. Med J Aust. 2024;220(4):181\u2013183. doi: 10.5694/mja2.52080. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2024/220/4/patient-blood-management-guideline-adults-critical-bleeding","Antunes C, Tian C, Copelin II EL. Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding. [Updated 2024 Aug 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470300/","Killeen RB, Tambe A. Acute Anemia. [Updated 2024 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537232/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16908"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T16:15:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-20T16:16:00+09